Answer suggests that the visible attribute is not the one that should be used, rather than the visible attribute, perhaps a class name is the one that should be used. A clean fix, as opposed to a hacky fix would be to use a class name that puts the modal behind the body on load and alters the z-index via CSS on button click (though this may still cause a visible jump in the layout). Here are some suggestions:

1. Use a class name to put the modal behind the body on load and alter the z-index with CSS on click. This will ensure that the modal is loaded behind the body on load, and its z-index is altered with CSS on click. You can add a class to the element in the `onShow` event that changes the z-index of the CSS. For example, you can use a class like `modal-loaded` and add this CSS rule:

```css
.modal-loaded {
    position: fixed;
}
```

This way, the modal is loaded behind the body and the z-index is altered with CSS on click.

Alternatively, you could programmatically resize the modal after the button is clicked. This would mean that the modal is shown and resized after the button is clicked, maintaining the layout. However, this method does involve JavaScript, which may cause a visible jump in the layout as the modal resizes. Given the constraints and the desire for a clean solution, here are a few steps that could be taken:

1. Load the modal with a class name that puts it behind the body on load.
2. Add JavaScript to alter the z-index with CSS on click.
3. Ensure to resize the modal after the button click, maintaining the layout.

Here is a code snippet to demonstrate a clean solution:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.modal-loaded {
    position: fixed;
    z-index: 9999;
}
</style>
<script>
window.onload = function() {
    document.querySelector('.modal').classList.add('modal-loaded');
}

document.querySelector('.modal').onshow = function() {
    document.querySelector('.modal').classList.remove('modal-loaded');
    document.querySelector('.modal').style.zIndex = 10000;
}
</script>
</head>
<body>
<div id="modal" class="modal">
    <!-- Modal content -->
</div>
</body>
</html>

This approach ensures that the modal is loaded behind the body on load, and its z-index is altered with CSS on click, avoiding a visible jump in the layout. The solution involves minimal change to the existing structure and leverages existing technologies to achieve a clean user experience. 

